abstract: Soybean exudates contain iron compounds which can be separated electrophoretically into anodic bands and eluted with water. Chromatography of the water extracts separated iron from chelating agents which were identified as malic acid and malonic acid. Hence organic acids seem to function in the translocation of iron in plants.

Results are presented of measurements of radon concentrations in the atmosphere at altitudes up to 80,000 ft, these were made near the equator and in the polar regions. The observations, combined with the vertical profiles of ozone and fission products whose origin is the stratosphere, suggest that a rising motion, rather than turbulent mixing, is the more likely mode of transfer in the upper atmosphere. (C.H.)
The number of nutritive hydranths in a slide-grown colony of this marine hydroid increases exponentially until sexual forms appear in the colony.

A method and apparatus for directly determining the density of solids is described. Essentially, density is determind by simultaneous measurement of the solid's volume by liquid displacement and of its weight by liquid head increase.

The methods of irreversible thermodynamics, applied to the problem of steady-state linear diffusion, lead to the conclusion that the flux across any system of parallel membranes or phase boundaries can be expressed as a linear function of the differences in electrochemical potential across the system. The presence of fixed charges, polarizable molecules, or electric fields does not alter the flux-force relation.
